{"id":"astro-ph/0509360","submitter":"Mariangela Bernardi","authors":"M. Bernardi, R. C. Nichol, R. K. Sheth, C. J. Miller, J. Brinkmann","title":"Evolution and environment of early-type galaxies","comments":"58 pages, 22 figures. Accepted by AJ. The full version of Tables 1,\n  2, 3, 4 and 7, 8 are available at\n  http://www.physics.upenn.edu/~bernardm/PAPERS/EnvEvol/TABLES/ A README file\n  (bernardi_TABLES.README) explains the content of the directory. The 925\n  composite spectra can be downloaded from\n  http://www.physics.upenn.edu/~bernardm/PAPERS/EnvEvol/SPECTRA/ A README file\n  (bernardi_COMPOSITES.README) explains the content of the directory. Table 9:\n  the ZP of the Age-sigma relation has been corrected","journal-ref":"Astron.J.131:1288-1317,2006","doi":"10.1086/499522","report-no":null,"categories":"astro-ph","license":null,"abstract":"  We study the photometric and spectral properties of 39320 early-type galaxies\nwithin the SDSS, as a function of both local environment and redshift. The\ndistance to the nearest cluster of galaxies and the distance to the 10th\nnearest luminous neighbor were used to define two extremes in environment. The\nproperties of early-type galaxies are weakly but significantly different in\nthese two extremes: objects in dense environments are less than ~1 Gyr older\nand alpha-enhanced by ~0.02 relative to their counterparts of the same velocity\ndispersion in less dense regions, but the metallicities show no dependence on\nenvironment. This suggests that, in dense regions, the stars in early-type\ngalaxies formed at slightly earlier times, and on a slightly shorter timescale,\nthan in less dense regions. In addition, objects at lower redshifts are older,\nbut have the same metallicities and alpha-enhancements as their counterparts of\nthe same sigma at higher redshifts, as expected if the low redshift sample is a\npassively-aged version of the sample at higher redshifts. These significant\nconclusions are derived from several pieces of evidence discussed in this\npaper, including the FP of early-types, the observed evolution of absorption\nlinestrengths (measured from a large ensemble of composite spectra which we\nprovide in tabular form) over small lookback times, and comparison with the\npredictions of single burst (non-solar abundance) stellar population synthesis\nmodels (which also indicate that age, metallicity and alpha-enhancement all\nincrease with velocity dispersion).\n","versions":[{"version":"v1","created":"Wed, 14 Sep 2005 18:24:37 GMT"},{"version":"v2","created":"Wed, 30 Nov 2005 16:16:44 GMT"}],"update_date":"2008-11-26"}
{"id":"astro-ph/0509371","submitter":"Hugo Martel","authors":"Hugo Martel (Universite Laval), Chris Brook (Universite Laval), Sean\n  McGee (Universite of Waterloo), Brad Gibson (Swinburne University), & Daisuke\n  Kawata (Carnegie Observatories)","title":"The Evolving Structure of Galactic Disks","comments":"Will appear in Proceedings of the 9th Asian Pacific Regional IAU\n  Meeting","journal-ref":null,"doi":null,"report-no":null,"categories":"astro-ph","license":null,"abstract":"  Observations suggest that the structural parameters of disk galaxies have not\nchanged greatly since redshift 1. We examine whether these observations are\nconsistent with a cosmology in which structures form hierarchically. We use\nSPH/N-body galaxy-scale simulations to simulate the formation and evolution of\nMilky-Way-like disk galaxies by fragmentation, followed by hierarchical\nmerging. The simulated galaxies have a thick disk, that forms in a period of\nchaotic merging at high redshift, during which a large amount of alpha-elements\nare produced, and a thin disk, that forms later and has a higher metallicity.\nOur simulated disks settle down quickly and do not evolve much since redshift\nz~1, mostly because no major mergers take place between z=1 and z=0. During\nthis period, the disk radius increases (inside-out growth) while its thickness\nremains constant. These results are consistent with observations of disk\ngalaxies at low and high redshift.\n","versions":[{"version":"v1","created":"Wed, 14 Sep 2005 17:11:28 GMT"}],"update_date":"2007-05-23"}
